SIMPLE: marble
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Marble
<hw>Mar"ble</hw> <pr>(m⟦aum⟧r"b'l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>marbel</ets>, <ets>marbre</ets>, F. <ets>marbre</ets>, L.
<ets>marmor</ets>, fr. Gr. <grk>ma`rmaros</grk>, fr.
<grk>marmai`rein</grk> to sparkle, flash. Cf. <er>Marmoreal</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A massive, compact limestone; a variety of calcite,
capable of being polished and used for architectural and ornamental
purposes. The color varies from white to black, being sometimes yellow,
red, and green, and frequently beautifully veined or clouded. The name
is also given to other rocks of like use and appearance, as serpentine
or verd antique marble, and less properly to polished porphyry, granite,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <col><b>Breccia marble</b></col> consists of limestone
fragments cemented together. -- <col><b>Ruin marble</b></col>, when
polished, shows forms resembling ruins, due to disseminated iron oxide.
-- <col><b>Shell marble</b></col> contains fossil shells. --
<col><b>Statuary marble</b></col> is a pure, white, fine-grained kind,
including <xex>Parian</xex> (from Paros) and <xex>Carrara</xex> marble.
If coarsely granular it is called <xex>saccharoidal</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A thing made of, or resembling, marble, as a work of
art, or record, in marble; or, in the plural, a collection of such
works; <as>as, the Arundel or Arundelian <ex>marbles</ex>; the Elgin
<ex>marbles</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A little ball of glass, marble, porcelain, or of
some other hard substance, used as a plaything by children; or, in the
plural, a child's game played with marbles.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Marble</xex> is also much used in self-explaining
compounds; when used figuratively in compounds it commonly means, hard,
cold, destitute of compassion or feeling; as,
<xex>marble-</xex>breasted, <xex>marble-</xex>faced,
<xex>marble-</xex>hearted.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Marble
<hw>Mar"ble</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Made of, or resembling,
marble; <as>as, a <ex>marble</ex> mantel; <ex>marble</ex>
paper.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Cold; hard; unfeeling; <as>as, a <ex>marble</ex>
breast or heart</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Marble
<hw>Mar"ble</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Marbled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Marbling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>marbrer</ets>. See <er>Marble</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To
stain or vein like marble; to variegate in color; <as>as, to
<ex>marble</ex> the edges of a book, or the surface of
paper</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marbled</ent>⟦br⟧
